<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Phlox covillei </i>is a compact, caespitose perennial herb growing to 10 cm tall. Plants have woody caudices with taproots and surface roots that represent a greater biomass than the aboveground biomass. Plants reproduce infrequently from seed when environmental conditions are favorable. Rhizomes and layering allow plants to expand (Billings 1974). The <i>Jepson Manual </i>(Hickman 1993) recognizes <i>P. condensata </i>to include <i>P. covillei, </i>but we follow USDA NRCS (2008), which recognizes both <i>P. covillei </i>and <i>P. condensata</i>. The ecological differences between <i>P. condensata, P. covillei, </i>and <i>P. pulvinata </i>are not well known (see the <i>Phlox pulvinata </i>alliance). The plants of <i>P. covillei </i>are tightly cushion-like; those of <i>P. pulvinata </i>are matted and not tightly cushion-like (Hickman 1993). <br/>
<br/>
The alliance is characteristic but not restricted to non-glaciated Eocene peneplain surfaces at the highest elevations of the Sierra Nevada and White Mountains. Lag gravel (well-drained mixtures of sand, pebbles, and cobbles and boulders) typically covers the soil, and patterned ground features, sorted circles, non-sorted circles, stone nets, and non-sorted strips may be present (Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf 2007). Stands have <i>Phlox covillei </i>and/or <i>Podistera nevadensis </i>present in the Sierra Nevada phase; <i>P. nevadensis </i>is absent in the White Mountains. Pemble (1970) and Taylor (1984) do not use <i>P. covillei </i>in the association names, but <i>P. covillei </i>is usually present. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
