    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dj). Stands occur in dolomite, limestone, and several non-calcareous substrates at the McAfee and White Mountain RNAs (Major and Taylor 1977, Travers 1993, see Cheng 2004) in the White Mountains. The <i>Phlox covillei-Ivesia shockleyi</i> association characterizes the dolomite barrens at White Mountain RNA. In mesic depressions, <i>I. shockleyi</i> decreases in constancy and is replaced by <i>Ericameria parryi</i> (Taylor 1976a, see Cheng 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Eo). Stands exist on both granitic and metamorphic substrates, including marble, such as those along ridges at Harvey Monroe Hall RNA (Taylor 1984, see Cheng 2004), above Convict Creek (Pemble 1970), in Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b), in several areas in the section (Dennis et al. 2004), and on Coyote Ridge (Wenk and Dawson 2007).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Expansion and contraction of stands in relation to elevation and more mesic alpine stands may be indicators of long-term climatic change. Alpine trails frequently cross through stands in the Sierra Nevada. </div>
</div>

    

    

